Factor `mutation.consequence` contains implicit NA, consider using `forcats::fct_explicit_na`Factor `mutation.consequence` contains implicit NA, consider using `forcats::fct_explicit_na`Factor `mutation.consequence` contains implicit NA, consider using `forcats::fct_explicit_na`Factor `mutation.consequence` contains implicit NA, consider using `forcats::fct_explicit_na`
  • loss of function
    Nonsense, frame-shifting indel, essential splice site mutation, whole gene deletion or any other mutation where functional analysis demonstrates clear reduction or loss of function (Source: Definitions of the terms used in the database)
  • all missense/in frame
    Where all the mutations described in the data source are either missense or in frame deletions and there is no evidence favoring either loss-of-function, activating or dominant negative effect (Source: Definitions of the terms used in the database)
  • uncertain
    Where the exact nature of the mutation is unclear or not recorded (Source: Definitions of the terms used in the database)
  • activating
    Mutation, usually missense that results in a constituative functional activation of the gene product (Source: Definitions of the terms used in the database)
  • dominant negative
    Mutation within one allele of a gene that creates a significantly greater deleterious effect on gene product function than a monoallelic loss of function mutation (Source: Definitions of the terms used in the database)
  • cis-regulatory or promotor mutation
    Mutation in cis-regulatory elements that lies out with the known transcription unit and promotor of the controlled gene (Source: Definitions of the terms used in the database)
  • 5_prime or 3_prime UTR mutation
    Mutation occured at 5 UTR or 3 UTR. 5 UTR is the portion of an mRNA from the 5 end to the position of the first codon used in translation. The 3 UTR is the portion of an mRNA from the 3 end of the mRNA to the position of the last codon used in translation. (Source: Definition of the UTR)
  • gain of function
    Mutation, usually missense that results in a constituative functional activation of the gene product `gain of function activating mutation. (Source: Definitions of the terms used in the database)
  • increased gene dosage
    Copy number variation that increases the functional dosage of the gene (Source: Definitions of the terms used in the database)

mutation.consequence uncertain item . uncertain mutation Where the exact nature of the mutation is unclear or not recorded. organ.specificity.list data p grouping . , uncertain mutation row mutation unclear not recorded mutation category . data filter function data .

a <- p %>% filter(!mutation.consequence == 'uncertain') %>% group_by(mutation.consequence, organ.specificity.list) %>% count() %>% arrange(desc(n))
a
a %>% ggplot(aes(x = organ.specificity.list, y = n)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + coord_flip() + xlab("") + facet_grid(~mutation.consequence)

data a plot loss of function, all missense/in frame, activating row data . mutation.consequence item others .

b <- p %>% filter(!mutation.consequence == 'uncertain') %>% mutate(mutation.consequence = gsub('dominant negative', 'others', mutation.consequence)) %>% mutate(mutation.consequence = gsub('cis-regulatory or promotor mutation', 'others', mutation.consequence)) %>% mutate(mutation.consequence = gsub('5_prime or 3_prime UTR mutation', 'others', mutation.consequence)) %>% mutate(mutation.consequence = gsub( 'increased gene dosage', 'others', mutation.consequence)) %>% mutate(mutation.consequence = gsub('part of contiguous gene duplication', 'others', mutation.consequence)) %>% group_by(mutation.consequence, organ.specificity.list) %>% count() %>% arrange(desc(n))
b
analysis_1 <- b %>% ggplot(aes(x = organ.specificity.list, y = n)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + coord_flip() + xlab("") + facet_grid(~mutation.consequence) + ggtitle("The number of genes sorted according to \nmutation consequence and organ specificity") + theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"), axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90), strip.text.x = element_text(size = 4))
